article.description:
Tamika Catchings scored 24 points and the
Indiana Fever used late free throws to defeat the Los Angeles
Sparks 71-67 Friday night despite going without a field goal for
the final six minutes.
article.headline: Indiana wins despite no FGs in final 6 minutes
article.linkText: Fever hang on to defeat Sparks
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indiana's Tamika Catchings wasn't where she
wanted to be in the final minute as her team held off a late charge
to beat the Los Angeles Sparks 71-67 Friday night.

Catchings fouled out with 56 seconds to play and had to watch
from the bench as the Fever survived a late rally to defeat the
Sparks for the first time.

Catchings contributed 24 points, a season-high four blocked
shots and led her team with six rebounds.

"When Tamika fouled out, other players stepped up," Indiana
coach Brian Winters said. "We made our free throws at the end,
everyone contributed, I felt like we grew a little more in this
game."

Los Angeles rallied from a 14-point deficit in the second half
as Indiana failed to score a field goal in the final 6 minutes, 32
seconds. Los Angeles tightened its defense and tied the game at 65
with 56.2 seconds to play when Catchings fouled out.

Lisa Leslie, whose eight points were her second-lowest total
this season, made her first free throw and missed the second as the
Sparks tried to take their first lead since 29-27 with 4:58 left in
the first half.

Indiana scored its final nine points on free throws. Deanna
Jackson, who contributed 10 points to the victory, hit two free
throws with 37 seconds remaining. The 6-foot-5 Leslie, defended by
6-4 Kelly Schumacher, then missed a short turnaround jumper and the
Fever's Stephanie White was fouled in a scramble for the loose
ball.

"It was a great finish," Jackson said. "We played with poise
and we didn't let the game get away from us."

White, who scored a season-high eight points, made both free
throws with 21 seconds to play. Reserve Tamecka Dixon, who topped
the Sparks with 14 points, brought the visitors within two points
again, but Schumacher sealed the victory by making two free throws
with 13.2 seconds to go.

The Sparks (8-6) had 23 turnovers, which Indiana (7-5) converted
into 24 points.

"We have an inability to make the easy play. It seems like we
are always going for the home-run play and we're not doing a very
good job," said Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper, whose team
missed 11 free throws. "The least of our worries are free-throw
shooting.

"But, when you are struggling to do the easy things, it would
just make sense that we would struggle at the line."

Delisha Milton-Jones scored the first nine points for the
Sparks, who took an early lead. But she scored only four more
points while missing six free throws.

Indiana had season-highs for blocked shots (9), free throws made
(26) and free-throw attempts (36).

Reserve Tamika Whitmore was the only other Sparks player in
double figures, scoring 11 points with the help of her first two
3-pointers of the season.

The Fever appeared to have the game under control with a 16-8
run to start the second half. Indiana built a 58-44 lead on a
3-pointer by Catchings with 10:19 to play.

Catchings had eight of her points -- including a pair of
3-pointers -- in the run.

Indiana led 38-36 after a foul-plagued first half that included
seven ties and seven lead changes. The teams shot a combined 32
free throws in the half and the Fever helped themselves by going
14-of-19, while the Sparks were 10-of-13.
